        "/{account}/{database}/{table}.rows": {
            "get": {
                "summary": "Get rows",
                "operationId": "getRows",
                "description": "Get rows from a table or a set of related tables. Supports data selection, projection, sorting and paging. \n\nSelection specifies how to filter output rows and projection defines the output fields. Their expressions may use fields from other tables than the table specified in the URL. The API will automatically join tables through foreign keys to obtain values for related columns. \n\nQuery syntax is largely borrowed from OData.\n#### Example\nQuery sandwich orders. Get sandwiches ordered in Q1 2015 and priced higher than $8.00. Return customer name, order date, total order amount, sandwich name and price.\n\n**Selection**\n  * orders.order_date btwn '2015-01-01', '2015-03-31'\n  * sandwiches.price ge 8\n\n\n**Projection** \n  * customers.name\n  * orders.order_date\n  * orders.total_amount\n  * sandwiches.name\n  * sandwiches.price\n  \n  \n    http://api.donkeylift.com/demo/sandwiches/orders.rows?$filter=order_date btwn '2015-01-01','2015-03-31'%09sandwiches.price ge 8.00&$select=id,order_date,sandwiches.name,sandwiches.price,total_amount,customers.name&$orderby=order_date,sandwiches.name\n\n\n\n### Selection \nSelection means filtering out rows. It is the equivalent of the WHERE clause in SQL. \n\nSelection is specificed by a set of filters. Filters are combined using AND logic, meaning rows must fulfill all filters to be returned in the result set. \n\nFields in filter expression may be prefixed by a table name to refer to other tables than the table in the URL. \n\nIf filter is blank, the result rows are not filtered at all.\nIndividual filter definition options follow.\n#### Syntax\n    [table].field {op} values\n\nEach filter has three parts: the table field it acts upon, the operator to apply to that field, and the values that parametrize the filter operation. \n\nIf table prefix is omitted, the field is assumed to be from the table in the URL.   \n\nOnly literals are supported as filter values. \n#### Operators\n##### eq / ne / gt / ge / lt / le\nEqual, Not equal, Greater than, Greater or equal than, Lesser than and Lesser or equal than operators. Operation parameter must be a single value.\n\n    Name eq 'Fred'\n    Product.Price le 100\n##### in / ex\nIn and Ex (not in) operators. Supports multiple values.\n\n    Country in 'Belgium','Netherlands','Luxemburg'\n    Product.Accessory ex 'Headset','Microphone'\n    \n##### btwn\nBetween operator. A convenience operator equivalent to 'greater or equal than and lesser or equal than'. Requires two values.\n\n    Price btwn 0.01,9.99\n    Name btwn 'A','D'\n\n##### search\nSearch operator. Search comes in two forms: search for values on a specific field or full text search on table.\n\nSearching on a specific field will first convert column values to text and search for values that *start* with the given search value. In order to search for values contained in the column, precede your search term with '*'.\n\nTo do full text search on the complete table specify as field value table.*\n\n\n    Description search 'Paris'\n    Description search '*aris'\n    Product.* search 'France'\n\n### Projection\nProjection means choosing specific fields for the output rows. It is the equivalent of the list of fields specified after the SELECT keyword in SQL. \n\nField names may be prefixed by a table name to join data from other tables than the table in the URL. \n\nIf table prefix is omitted, the field is assumed to be from the table in the URL.   \n\nIf projection is blank, all fields from the url table are returned.\n### Ordering\nOrdering sorts result rows according to one or more result fields, it is the  equivalent of the ORDERBY clause in SQL. \n\nOrdering is specificed a list of table fields; each optionally followed by the asc or desc keyword to specify ordering direction. \n\nTable fields in ordering clauses must be part of the result rows as defined by the projection. \n#### Syntax\n    [table].field (asc|desc)\n\n    \n",
                "parameters": [
                    {
                        "name": "account",
                        "in": "path",
                        "description": "database account",
                        "required": true,
                        "type": "string"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "database",
                        "in": "path",
                        "description": "database",
                        "required": true,
                        "type": "string"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "table",
                        "in": "path",
                        "description": "database table",
                        "required": true,
                        "type": "string"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "$filter",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "array of row filters.",
                        "required": false,
                        "type": "array",
                        "collectionFormat": "tsv",
                        "items": {
                            "type": "string"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "$select",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "array of table fields.",
                        "required": false,
                        "type": "array",
                        "collectionFormat": "csv",
                        "items": {
                            "type": "string"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "$orderby",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "array of order clauses.",
                        "required": false,
                        "type": "array",
                        "collectionFormat": "csv",
                        "items": {
                            "type": "string"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "$skip",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "skip this number of rows.",
                        "required": false,
                        "type": "integer"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "$top",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "max number of rows to be returned.",
                        "required": false,
                        "type": "integer"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "format",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "define row output format. currently supported are json, csv.",
                        "required": false,
                        "default": "json",
                        "type": "string"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "counts",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "Obtain total number of rows for the query. \n##### Rationale\nThe API can return not only the result rows, but also counts on the total number of rows of the query resultset as well as the total number of rows of the queried table (with no filters). \nIf the API does not return the complete resultset (because of internal paging limits), it would also return the URL for the next set of result rows (pagination).\n",
                        "required": false,
                        "default": 0,
                        "type": "integer"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "debug",
                        "in": "query",
                        "description": "obtain debug information around underlying SQL execution.",
                        "required": false,
                        "default": 0,
                        "type": "integer"
                    }
                ],
                "tags": [
                    "table"
                ],
                "responses": {
                    "200": {
                        "description": "A row result set",
                        "schema": {
                            "$ref": "#/definitions/ResponseRows"
                        }
                    },
                    "default": {
                        "description": "Unexpected error",
                        "schema": {
                            "$ref": "#/definitions/Error"
                        }
                    }
                }
